# Verify build, then Docker (decide, then act)

## Always: web verification

After **meaningful changes** under `apps/web` (TS/TSX/JS, config that affects build, `package.json`), run **`npm run build`** with cwd **`apps/web`**. Fix failures before treating the task as done.

Skip a redundant build only when the change cannot affect the Next app (e.g. markdown-only, unrelated folder).

## Rebuild everything (default after code changes)

When edits touched **`apps/web`**, **`services/ml-api`**, any **`Dockerfile`**, or **`docker-compose.yml`**, assume Docker users need **fresh images**. From the directory that contains **`docker-compose.yml`** (repo **`oracleeyes/oracleeyes`**, not the monorepo parent):

```bash
docker compose up --build -d
```

That rebuilds **all** services that define a `build:` (`web`, `ml-api`) and recreates containers. Prefer this **full** rebuild whenever you are **unsure** or the diff spans more than one service.

Use a **scoped** rebuild only when you are certain only one image changed:

```bash
docker compose up --build -d web    # only apps/web / web Dockerfile
docker compose up --build -d ml-api  # only services/ml-api
```

Do **not** skip rebuilding after implementation work and then only suggest commands to the user—**run** build/compose yourself when the task is in-repo code and Docker is in scope (per user rules).

## Docker: ask yourself first

Before running compose, **briefly decide** whether containers need updating:

| Run **`docker compose up --build -d`** (full) when… | Skip Docker when… |
|------------------------------------------------------|-------------------|
| **`apps/web`** or **`services/ml-api`** or **Docker/compose** changed | Change is **docs-only**, **tests-only**, or **outside** those paths |
| You are **unsure** which service’s image is stale | User is clearly on **pure local** `npm run dev` + host ML and did not ask about Docker |
| User asked to **refresh / rebuild / restart** the stack | — |

- **Rebuild** (`--build`) when image contents or build args changed.  
- **`docker compose restart <service>`** only when the image is unchanged and you only need a process restart.

## Examples

```bash
cd apps/web && npm run build
cd /path/to/oracleeyes && docker compose up --build -d   # oracleeyes/ folder with docker-compose.yml
```

Do not skip **`npm run build`** for web work just because Docker will run `next build` again—local build catches errors faster.
